        // Article 1: PV Systems Classification
        'article_1_title' => 'Photovoltaic Solar Energy: Plant and System Classification',
        'article_1_excerpt' => 'Photovoltaic (PV) energy represents the technology of converting solar radiation directly into electrical energy. PV systems vary in design and function to meet different needs.',
        'article_1_content' => 'Photovoltaic Solar Energy: Plant and System Classification\n\nPhotovoltaic (PV) energy represents the technology of converting solar radiation directly into electrical energy. PV systems vary in design and function to meet different needs, and are primarily classified based on their relationship to the public electricity grid or operational purpose.\n\nFirst: Common Core Components\n\nAll solar systems depend on two basic components to generate electricity:\n\n1. Photovoltaic Panels (PV Panels): Units consisting of solar cells to absorb photons and convert light energy to direct current (DC).\n\n2. Inverter: The device responsible for converting direct current (DC) produced by panels to alternating current (AC) matching grid current or household electrical appliances.\n\nSecond: System Classification by Grid Connection\n\nSolar power plant types are distinguished based on their connection mechanism to the public electricity grid:\n\n1. On-Grid/Grid-Tied Systems:\n   - Definition: The most common systems, working in complete parallel and integration with the public electricity grid.\n   - Operation Mechanism: Generated power is consumed directly; if production exceeds consumption, surplus is exported to the grid and recorded in customer\'s favor via Net Metering mechanism.\n   - Technical Considerations: Does not contain storage batteries, and stops working automatically when public grid fails to ensure maintenance crew safety (protection feature called Anti-islanding).\n\n2. Off-Grid/Stand-Alone Systems:\n   - Definition: Systems designed to operate completely independently without any connection to public grid.\n   - Operation Mechanism: Generated power is directed first to feed loads, then surplus to battery bank storage, which is the most important element to ensure power supply continuity at night or cloudy days.\n   - Application: Ideal for remote locations, areas without electrical infrastructure, or requiring complete independence.\n\n3. Hybrid Systems:\n   - Definition: Advanced solutions combining advantages of both previous systems: public grid connection and storage battery presence.\n   - Operation Mechanism: System works intelligently to determine power priorities: immediate consumption, battery charging, and exporting surplus to grid. This system provides Back-up Power feature, where it automatically switches to battery feeding in case of public grid failure.\n   - Application: Used in vital facilities that cannot tolerate power interruption and require maximum flexibility and safety.\n\nThird: Specialized Applications - Solar Irrigation Systems\n\nSolar water pumping systems are one of the important applications depending on photovoltaic technology:\n\n- Operation Mechanism: Panels generate power, directed through Variable Frequency Drive (VFD) directly to water pump. System works proportionally, where pumping power increases with solar radiation intensity increase.\n- Technical Advantage: These systems usually do not need batteries, but depend on direct work during daytime hours, making them cost and operation effective in agricultural sectors.\n- Use: Providing irrigation water, extracting groundwater, and circulating water in farms and remote locations, eliminating need for diesel generators or distant electrical connections.',
        
        // Article 2: Solar Water Heaters Guide
        'article_2_title' => 'The Most Important Things to Know About Solar Water Heaters and Their Types',
        'article_2_excerpt' => 'Solar water heaters are a proven engineering solution to reduce dependence on traditional energy sources for water heating. Before considering installing any system, there are fundamental facts about this technology and its types that every consumer should be aware of.',
        'article_2_content' => 'The Most Important Things to Know About Solar Water Heaters and Their Types\n\nSolar water heaters are a proven engineering solution to reduce dependence on traditional energy sources for water heating. Before considering installing any system, there are fundamental facts about this technology and its types that every consumer should be aware of.\n\n1. Basic Principle: Converting Radiation to Heat\n\nThe central idea of solar heater is that it is a thermal system not electrical. Main parts work to convert solar radiation to heat, and this heat is transferred and stored in an insulated tank. This means system efficiency depends on available radiation amount and thermal insulation quality of collectors and tank.\n\n2. Collector Types: When to Choose This and When That?\n\nChoice between solar collector types is not a matter of quality as much as adaptation to climatic and operational conditions.\n\nCollector Type | Main Performance Advantages | Optimal Application & Notes\n\nEvacuated Tubes:\n- Very high thermal efficiency: Distinguished by superior insulation thanks to air evacuation, reducing thermal loss.\n- Ideal for cold areas or those experiencing large temperature variations. Suitable for facilities requiring very high water temperatures (such as hotels and restaurants).\n\nFlat Plate Collectors:\n- Structural durability and relatively lower initial cost. Easy integration with building\'s architectural appearance.\n- Best choice for moderate and sunny areas, where required efficiency is less intense, and focus is on durability.\n\n3. System Components Necessary for Efficiency\n\nTo ensure efficient system operation, attention must be paid to these components:\n\n- Storage Tank: Insulation quality in tank is key to maintaining water heat at night. Better insulation means less need for auxiliary heater.\n\n- Back-up Heater: All solar systems must contain auxiliary electric or gas heater. This heater ensures required water temperature on completely cloudy days or during very high consumption periods.\n\n- Circulation Principle: Systems can work with Natural circulation (Thermosiphon) where no pump is needed, or Forced circulation (Active System) using pump and control unit, which is the best choice for large projects or when tank is far from collectors.\n\n4. Important Investment Facts\n\n- Lifespan: Operational life of good solar heaters exceeds 15 to 25 years.\n- Savings: Solar heater contributes to covering between 60% to 80% of annual hot water needs, ensuring rapid reduction in energy bill.\n- Maintenance: Maintenance requirements are low and usually limited to simple inspection every few years.',
        
        // Article 3: Solar Energy FAQ
        'article_3_title' => 'Solar Energy Questions and Answers',
        'article_3_excerpt' => 'Comprehensive answers to the most common questions about photovoltaic systems and solar water heaters.',
        'article_3_content' => 'Solar Energy Questions and Answers\n\nFirst: Questions About Photovoltaic (PV) Systems\n\nQ: Do solar panels work in cloudy or rainy weather?\nA: Yes, panels produce electricity using solar radiation, even if indirect. However, production efficiency decreases significantly (may reach 10-25% of normal production) compared to sunny days.\n\nQ: What is the expected lifespan of solar panels?\nA: High-quality panels are usually warranted for 25 years regarding performance efficiency, where most companies guarantee production will not be less than 80% of original efficiency after this period.\n\nQ: What is the difference between On-Grid and Hybrid systems?\nA: On-Grid system does not contain batteries and depends entirely on public grid. Hybrid system combines grid connection and storage battery presence, providing Back-up power in case of power outage.\n\nQ: Do solar systems require expensive maintenance?\nA: No, maintenance is very minimal. Usually limited to cleaning panels several times a year and simple periodic inspection of electrical components to ensure operating efficiency.\n\nQ: Can I sell surplus electricity to the grid?\nA: Yes, this is done via Net Metering mechanism, where produced surplus is recorded in customer\'s favor against drawing electricity when needed (at night or in winter).\n\nSecond: Questions About Solar Water Heaters\n\nQ: Does solar heater work at night?\nA: Yes, water heat is maintained at night thanks to thermally insulated tank excellently. Also an auxiliary electric heater is available that works automatically to ensure required temperature if stored water temperature drops.\n\nQ: Can solar heater be relied upon in winter?\nA: Yes, efficiency may decrease slightly due to radiation decrease, but efficiently designed systems (especially evacuated tubes) continue working. When necessary, auxiliary electric heater is activated to ensure constant temperature.\n\nQ: What is the lifespan of solar heater tank?\nA: Entire system lifespan can reach 20 years or more, depending on component and material quality used (such as steel quality and tank insulation).\n\nQ: Do I need a pump to install solar heater?\nA: This depends on type. Natural circulation systems (Thermosiphon) do not need pump. Forced circulation systems (Active System) require small pump to transfer fluid between collector and tank, which is best for long distances or large projects.\n\nQ: Is solar heater suitable for freezing temperature areas?\nA: Yes, special fluids (Anti-Freeze) are used in circulation systems (instead of regular water) in these areas to prevent fluid freezing inside collectors and pipes and protect system from damage.',
